00:07:03.970 --> 00:07:11.360
A recent study defined humanitarian
crises as quote, "Any situation

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:17.800
in which there is widespread threat
to life, physical safety, health,

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:23.220
or basic subsistence that is
beyond the coping capacity

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:28.370
of the individuals and
communities in which they reside."

00:07:28.370 --> 00:07:34.390
I can assure you from some of my
visits to places like South Sudan,

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:40.540
Rwanda, that people displaced by
war, especially those displaced

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:46.360
in vast numbers, often
face threats that are --

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:49.180
go beyond their coping capacity.

00:07:49.180 --> 00:07:52.450
The very opposite of
the kind of support

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:55.610
that I received here in the fall.

00:07:55.610 --> 00:08:00.120
My concern this afternoon is
with our ethical responsibilities

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:04.290
to people who are facing
these humanitarian crises.

00:08:04.290 --> 00:08:10.460 position:56%
And I'm using the term humanitarian,
in a way shaped by the principles

00:08:10.460 --> 00:08:13.730
of the International
Committee of the Red Cross.

00:08:13.730 --> 00:08:15.760
Some people regard the ICRC

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:19.320
as the gold standard
of humanitarian action.

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:21.800
But in the principles of
the international committee

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:27.000
of the red cross, humanity is used
in a way that has two meanings.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:31.560
It refers first of all to
the whole of human kind.

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:36.100
To act with humanity therefore,
calls for inclusive concern

00:08:36.100 --> 00:08:41.070
for all members of the human
family, on the basis of their need.

00:08:41.070 --> 00:08:45.360
Not because of their
nationality, race, or religion.

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:54.530
Secondly, humanity is a spirit that
is sometimes called humaneness.

00:08:54.530 --> 00:08:58.610
It is compassion for
those who are suffering.

00:08:58.610 --> 00:09:02.580
A virtue quite similar
to Christian love.

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:07.570
Humanity in this sense, seeks
to alleviate serious distress,

00:09:07.570 --> 00:09:11.840
especially when that distress
exceeds the coping capacity

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:14.820
of those who are affected.

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:20.570 position:56%
The scope of humanitarian crises has
grown dramatically in recent years,

00:09:20.570 --> 00:09:27.090
and is evident from the growing
number of people displaced by war.

00:09:27.090 --> 00:09:32.170 position:56%
United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees tells us that the number

00:09:32.170 --> 00:09:36.600
of people displaced by
war, intrastate strife,

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:40.080
and human rights violations,
reached 59

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:47.120
and a half million globally
last year, 8.3 million more

00:09:47.120 --> 00:09:50.080
than just a year earlier.

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:52.750
This is the largest
increase in the number

00:09:52.750 --> 00:09:58.070
of displaced persons ever
recorded for a single year.

00:09:58.070 --> 00:10:04.260 position:56%
The number of displaced people, it
is estimated, will exceed 61 million

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:08.070
by the end of this year, 2016.

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:11.680
These people have no
choice about moving.

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:16.180
The conditions they face,
often due to conflict,

00:10:16.180 --> 00:10:20.680
put their most basic
human rights on the line,

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:23.450 position:56%
often including their right to life.

00:10:23.450 --> 00:10:27.680
For example, the massive
displacement in the eastern part

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:31.670
of the Democratic Republic
of the Congo, has been caused

00:10:31.670 --> 00:10:37.390
by ethnic conflict, armed
rebellion, and resulting disease

00:10:37.390 --> 00:10:40.840
and malnutrition that
has led to more

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:45.690
than 5 million deaths
over the past decade.

00:10:46.890 --> 00:10:50.940
Well, what can we say about our
responsibilities in the face

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:55.090
of these crises, and the
suffering they cause?

00:10:55.090 --> 00:10:58.380
As the number of people
seeking asylum

00:10:58.380 --> 00:11:02.610
from such grave threats
has risen in recent years,

00:11:02.610 --> 00:11:08.450
secular political philosophers
such as Joseph Carens,

00:11:08.450 --> 00:11:13.900
and refugee scholars such as
Philip Marfleet, have been arguing

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:21.380
that the time has come to consider
making borders fully open to all

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:27.870
who are fleeing from
persecution, conflict, or disaster.

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:32.260
In a similar way, similar
spirit, several years ago,

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:38.560 position:56%
the philosopher Martha Nussbaum
argued that a cosmopolitan community

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:44.410
of all human beings, should have
primacy over narrower communities,

00:11:44.410 --> 00:11:49.800
defined in terms of nationality,
ethnicity, or religion.

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:54.340
Indeed, Nussbaum called
nationality, in her words,

00:11:54.340 --> 00:11:59.230
"a morally irrelevant
characteristic of personhood."

00:11:59.230 --> 00:12:06.980
Such a cosmopolitan vision can be
given Christian religious backing.

00:12:06.980 --> 00:12:14.160 position:56%
For example, during his recent visit
to the island of Lesbos in Greece,

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:19.850
on the border with Turkey, Pope
Francis told Syrian refugees there,

00:12:19.850 --> 00:12:23.280
who were seeking entrance
to Europe, that quote,

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:28.440
"God created humankind
to be one family."

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:32.400
The pope then called
Europe to "Build bridges

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:35.800
and to recoil from
putting up walls."

00:12:35.800 --> 00:12:43.320
And then he turned around and took
12 Syrian refugees, all Muslim,

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:46.910
back to the Vatican
with him in his plane.

00:12:46.910 --> 00:12:50.830
Pope Francis was drawing on
the Book of Genesis' teaching

00:12:50.830 --> 00:12:55.310
that all persons are created in the
image of God, making them brothers

00:12:55.310 --> 00:12:58.300 position:56%
and sisters in a single human family

00:12:58.300 --> 00:13:00.820
that reaches across
national borders.

00:13:00.820 --> 00:13:06.350
The universality of human
dignity in a similar way,

00:13:06.350 --> 00:13:13.000
led Pope John the 23rd back
in 1963, to insist, I quote,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:18.240 position:56%
"The fact that one is a citizen of
a particular state, does not detract

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:23.240
in any way from one's membership
in the human family as a whole,

00:13:23.240 --> 00:13:27.570
nor from one's membership
in the world community."

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:34.900
So, a strong defense of the
common humanity among all of us

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:39.370
that should affect our
response to people in crisis.

00:13:39.370 --> 00:13:45.640
Nevertheless, this philosophical
and Christian universalism,

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:51.300
calls not only for the support
of the unity of the human family,

00:13:51.300 --> 00:13:55.620
but it also calls, I would
submit, that we are obligated

00:13:55.620 --> 00:14:02.400
to respect the differences among
people's cultures and nations.

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:03.710
In her recent writings,

00:14:03.710 --> 00:14:10.600 position:56%
Martha Nussbaum now draw upon
Rothias [phonetic] and Kant to argue

00:14:10.600 --> 00:14:15.810
that "People exercise their
freedom and express their dignity

00:14:15.810 --> 00:14:21.480
when they shape the institutions
of their own nation state."

00:14:21.480 --> 00:14:26.980
Protecting the independence
of accountable states is thus,

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:32.510
for Nussbaum today, a way
of protecting human dignity.

00:14:32.510 --> 00:14:37.130
In a similar way, Christian
theologians like St. Augustin

00:14:37.130 --> 00:14:40.390
and St. Thomas Aquinas,
have affirmed that

00:14:40.390 --> 00:14:46.250
"There is a Christian duty to love
all human beings as our neighbors,

00:14:46.250 --> 00:14:51.990
but also a duty in Christian
love, to show distinctive concern

00:14:51.990 --> 00:14:56.440
for those with whom we have special
relationships," such as members

00:14:56.440 --> 00:15:00.860
of our families or
our fellow citizens.

00:15:00.860 --> 00:15:04.660
Christian ethics thus
acknowledges our special duties

00:15:04.660 --> 00:15:06.930
toward co-citizens.

00:15:06.930 --> 00:15:11.370
While also forbidding actions
that effectively treat those

00:15:11.370 --> 00:15:14.430
from other communities
who are in grave need,

00:15:14.430 --> 00:15:18.900
as if they were nonhuman
or nonpersons.

00:15:18.900 --> 00:15:21.430
A key issue for the
ethics of response

00:15:21.430 --> 00:15:25.780
to people facing humanitarian
crisis, is thus what kind

00:15:25.780 --> 00:15:31.660
of priorities should we be giving
to this universal concern for all

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:36.810 position:56%
and this special concern for those
with whom we have special relations?

00:15:36.810 --> 00:15:40.410
A special concern, a set of
priorities, that Augustin

00:15:40.410 --> 00:15:45.610
and Aquinas call the "ordo
amoris," the ordering of our loves.

00:15:45.610 --> 00:15:50.450
The humanitarian crises of today
call us to reflect carefully

00:15:50.450 --> 00:15:54.740
on the relative weights of the
obligations and rights that arise

00:15:54.740 --> 00:15:59.200
from our common humanity and
from our distinctive identities.

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:03.500
What I want to do today is to
suggest several priorities,

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:09.300
focusing first on our negative
duties that are relevant

00:16:09.300 --> 00:16:15.380 position:56%
to the crises caused by war today,
and then on several positive duties,

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:19.430
to aid those who are facing crises.

00:16:19.430 --> 00:16:23.560
Key negative duties relative to
the humanitarian crises caused

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:26.320 position:56%
by conflict today can be highlighted

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:32.620
by drawing upon the moral tradition
known as the "Just War Ethic."

00:16:32.620 --> 00:16:37.720
This tradition distinguishes
between morally legitimate

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:40.860
and morally illegitimate
uses of force.

00:16:40.860 --> 00:16:46.150 position:56%
So it should probably be called
"The Just and Unjust War Tradition,"

00:16:46.150 --> 00:16:50.500
rather than suggesting that it
implies that all wars are just.

00:16:50.500 --> 00:16:53.110
This tradition has roots
in Christian thought,

00:16:53.110 --> 00:16:58.630
especially in Catholicism, but it
also overlaps with the tradition

00:16:58.630 --> 00:17:02.450
of the International
Law of Armed Conflict.

00:17:02.450 --> 00:17:08.500
In its modern form, the Just/Unjust
War Tradition draws a sharp line

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:13.220
between force used in the
defense of human rights,

00:17:13.220 --> 00:17:17.270
and force used to violate
human rights.

00:17:17.270 --> 00:17:21.610
The U.S. Ad Bellum of Just
Cause, requires that requires

00:17:21.610 --> 00:17:25.910
that force be strictly
limited to defending the rights

00:17:25.910 --> 00:17:30.770
of innocent persons to
life, freedom, and security.

00:17:30.770 --> 00:17:34.760
And the rights of nation
states to self-determination

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:37.760
and territorial integrity.

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:43.480
Conversely, there is a negative
duty not to use force aggressively

00:17:43.480 --> 00:17:48.200
against other people's or to
deny them their political freedom

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:50.520
to exploit them economically

00:17:50.520 --> 00:17:53.610
or because they are
culturally different.

00:17:53.610 --> 00:17:58.150
Violation of these negative
duties is both immoral,

00:17:58.150 --> 00:18:03.550
and according to international
law, criminal.

00:18:03.550 --> 00:18:06.930
Sadly, this is just what happened

00:18:06.930 --> 00:18:12.390
in perhaps the worst humanitarian
crisis of recent times:

00:18:12.390 --> 00:18:19.000
the Rwanda genocide of 1994,
where force was massively used

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:25.550
to deny the most basic rights
of the Tutsi people in Rwanda.

00:18:25.550 --> 00:18:31.240
It was also appallingly violated
in the slaughter at Srebrenica

00:18:31.240 --> 00:18:34.600
where thousands of
Bosnian Muslims were killed

00:18:34.600 --> 00:18:39.720
because of their identity
as Bosnian Muslims,

00:18:39.720 --> 00:18:43.520
as part of an ethnic cleansing.

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:48.770
Similarly, the Just War
norms also forbid direct

00:18:48.770 --> 00:18:52.120
and intentional attacks
on civilians,

00:18:52.120 --> 00:18:56.880
as well as collateral harm to
civilians that is disproportionate

00:18:56.880 --> 00:18:59.290
to the good being sought.

00:18:59.290 --> 00:19:02.270
International law sets
forth similar prohibitions

00:19:02.270 --> 00:19:04.160
in the Geneva Conventions,

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:08.860
which insist that civilians must
be distinguished from soldiers

00:19:08.860 --> 00:19:11.980
and protected, both
from direct attack

00:19:11.980 --> 00:19:15.950
and from disproportionate
collateral harm.

00:19:15.950 --> 00:19:22.470
Violations of standards are war
crimes, and can become crimes

00:19:22.470 --> 00:19:28.110
against humanity, if they are
widespread and systematic.

00:19:28.110 --> 00:19:33.050
Regrettably, some recent
conflicts in our world today,

00:19:33.050 --> 00:19:39.250
have become humanitarian crises
precisely because of violations

00:19:39.250 --> 00:19:43.250
of these moral and
legal prohibitions.

00:19:43.250 --> 00:19:51.340
For example, tactics used in the
civil war that began in South Sudan

00:19:51.340 --> 00:19:55.790 position:56%
in December, 2013, just a short time

00:19:55.790 --> 00:20:00.750
after South Sudan had become
an independent country,

00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:04.910
the tactics used then have
regularly violated the rights

00:20:04.910 --> 00:20:07.670
of civilians to security.

00:20:07.670 --> 00:20:12.920
Human Rights Watch and a U.N.
panel of experts both concluded

00:20:12.920 --> 00:20:17.750
that the government of South Sudan
and the opposition forces as well,

00:20:17.750 --> 00:20:22.230
had quote, "Committed extraordinary
acts of cruelty that amount

00:20:22.230 --> 00:20:28.100
to war crimes, and in some
cases, crimes against humanity."

00:20:28.100 --> 00:20:33.040
Because of this mayhem,
by July 2015,

00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:40.070
over 1.6 million South Sudanese
had become internally displaced,

00:20:40.070 --> 00:20:45.150
and over three-quarters of a
million had become refugees.

00:20:45.150 --> 00:20:51.310
The strategies and tactics used
by both sides in South Sudan,

00:20:51.310 --> 00:20:56.920
have themselves turned
South Sudan into a situation

00:20:56.920 --> 00:21:00.350
of grave humanitarian emergency.

00:21:00.350 --> 00:21:05.080
The Syrian crisis reinforces
the conclusion

00:21:05.080 --> 00:21:08.860
that armed conflict can
lead to humanitarian crisis

00:21:08.860 --> 00:21:11.600
when the adversaries
violate their duty not

00:21:11.600 --> 00:21:14.460
to attack the basic
rights of civilians.

00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:18.690
The U.N.'s Independent
Commission of Inquiry on Syria,

00:21:18.690 --> 00:21:23.750
concluded that quote, "War
crimes, crimes against humanity,

00:21:23.750 --> 00:21:27.290
and human rights violations,
were so severe

00:21:27.290 --> 00:21:32.750
that the Syrian reality should
shock the conscience of humanity."

00:21:32.750 --> 00:21:34.570
These violations have led

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:38.870
to the single largest forced
migration in recent history.

00:21:38.870 --> 00:21:43.150
The flight of refugees has
threatened the stability

00:21:43.150 --> 00:21:46.810
of neighboring countries,
including Turkey,

00:21:46.810 --> 00:21:51.760 position:56%
which today hosts the single largest
number of refugees of any country

00:21:51.760 --> 00:21:55.190
in the world, Lebanon where one

00:21:55.190 --> 00:21:59.000
out of every four persons
inside the boundaries

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:04.110
of Lebanon is a Syrian
refugee, and Jordan.

00:22:04.110 --> 00:22:09.750
Syrian displacement has also as
we know, strained the politics

00:22:09.750 --> 00:22:15.070
of the European Union
in very recent months.

00:22:15.070 --> 00:22:19.440
The International Criminal
Court was established in 1998,

00:22:19.440 --> 00:22:23.540
to hold people accountable
for violations of standards

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:26.370
of international law, like these.

00:22:26.370 --> 00:22:30.250
The Rome Statute that created
the court, gave it jurisdiction

00:22:30.250 --> 00:22:34.800
over genocide, crimes
against humanity, war crimes,

00:22:34.800 --> 00:22:36.100
and the crime of aggression.

00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:41.990
The ICC has so far not been
able to bring to trial some

00:22:41.990 --> 00:22:46.610
of those it has charged with
such atrocities, due to its lack

00:22:46.610 --> 00:22:49.850 position:56%
of effective enforcement mechanisms.

00:22:49.850 --> 00:22:56.940
For example, Omar al-Bashir of
Jordan, Khartoum, a northern part

00:22:56.940 --> 00:23:01.740 position:56%
of what used to be the one Jordan,
faces charges of genocide and crimes

00:23:01.740 --> 00:23:06.410
against humanity for his
actions in the Darfur Region.

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:11.160
But obtaining his arrest
has so far been impossible.

00:23:11.160 --> 00:23:14.720 position:56%
Although he better not go back to
South Africa after a recent decision

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:18.090
of the South African supreme court,
that he should have been arrested

00:23:18.090 --> 00:23:20.830
when he was there the last time.

00:23:20.830 --> 00:23:25.320
Charges against Uhuru Kenyatta
of Kenya had to be dropped

00:23:25.320 --> 00:23:29.990
because the International Criminal
Court prosecutor was unable

00:23:29.990 --> 00:23:33.140
to get witnesses to testify,

00:23:33.140 --> 00:23:38.450
largely because most people think
their lives are on the line,

00:23:38.450 --> 00:23:41.990
or that some of them had
been massively bribed.

00:23:41.990 --> 00:23:46.970
Nevertheless, the court has had
success in some other cases,

00:23:46.970 --> 00:23:51.260
and other international
criminal tribunals have succeeded

00:23:51.260 --> 00:23:56.350
in bringing other people who
conducted these kinds of atrocities

00:23:56.350 --> 00:24:00.940
to account for their actions.

00:24:00.940 --> 00:24:05.540
These moves by some of these
international criminal tribunals,

00:24:05.540 --> 00:24:10.780
at least encourage me to think
that accountability for these kinds

00:24:10.780 --> 00:24:14.030
of violations is increasing.

00:24:14.030 --> 00:24:18.710
Duties not to violate basic
rights in conflict are more likely

00:24:18.710 --> 00:24:22.180
to be enforced today
than in the past.

00:24:22.180 --> 00:24:24.860
Although we're far from
where we should be.

00:24:24.860 --> 00:24:28.830
And those who violate such norms,
are less likely to get away

00:24:28.830 --> 00:24:32.680
with it today than
they were in the past,

00:24:32.680 --> 00:24:35.940
but with still a long way to go.

00:24:35.940 --> 00:24:39.000
Regrettably, we have learned
from history, and from insight

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:43.010
in the human moral weakness
that threats to human rights

00:24:43.010 --> 00:24:47.270
of this sort are probably
going to continue.

00:24:47.270 --> 00:24:53.200 position:56%
This raises the question of what
positive obligations we have to come

00:24:53.200 --> 00:24:58.390
to the assistance of those who
face crisis level suffering,

00:24:58.390 --> 00:25:01.110
because of their violation
of human rights.

00:25:01.110 --> 00:25:04.230
If people fail to follow
their negative duties not

00:25:04.230 --> 00:25:07.940
to commit these crimes, what
kind of positive duty do we have

00:25:07.940 --> 00:25:12.030
to actually take some
action to come to their aid?

00:25:12.030 --> 00:25:15.740
Here, I want to draw on
a mode of moral analysis

00:25:15.740 --> 00:25:21.510 position:56%
that was originally developed in
the 1970s, in the context of debates

00:25:21.510 --> 00:25:26.250
about who had duties to
eliminate the apartheid regime

00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:30.940
that separated South African
people by race, and did such harm

00:25:30.940 --> 00:25:34.290
to so many Black South
Africans for so many years.

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:40.390 position:56%
Some maintain that those who had not
created the apartheid system had no

00:25:40.390 --> 00:25:42.560
duty to try to change it.

00:25:42.560 --> 00:25:45.400
It was the South African's
duty to change the regime,

00:25:45.400 --> 00:25:49.200
not us Americans or Europeans.

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:53.320
But a very different
ethical approach was proposed

00:25:53.320 --> 00:25:56.210
by several scholars
at Yale University,

00:25:56.210 --> 00:26:00.950 position:56%
who argued that under certain
circumstances, persons, communities,

00:26:00.950 --> 00:26:04.680
or institutions can
have positive duties

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:09.890
to help remedy harms they
themselves did not cause.

00:26:09.890 --> 00:26:14.320
They called their approach,
the Kew Gardens Principles,

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:17.090
for it arose from reflection
by these group --

00:26:17.090 --> 00:26:20.670
by these scholars at Yale, on
a tragic case that occurred

00:26:20.670 --> 00:26:25.870
in the Kew Garden section of New
York City, way back in the mid-60s.

00:26:25.870 --> 00:26:27.370
According to press reports,

00:26:27.370 --> 00:26:33.470
a young woman named Kitty Genovese
was viciously assaulted, stabbed,

00:26:33.470 --> 00:26:38.610
and died a slow death while
38 nearby people watched

00:26:38.610 --> 00:26:40.100
and did nothing.

00:26:40.100 --> 00:26:43.950
Some failing to call the police.

00:26:43.950 --> 00:26:47.180
It has since been learned
that the initial reports

00:26:47.180 --> 00:26:52.380
of what happened were not entirely
accurate, but the public outrage

00:26:52.380 --> 00:26:56.630
at what happened to Kitty Genovese
stimulated by the press reports,

00:26:56.630 --> 00:27:01.340
points to the fact that most
people anyway, have a conviction

00:27:01.340 --> 00:27:08.170
that it is not enough not to
cause harm, in some situations,

00:27:08.170 --> 00:27:13.390
one has a duty to come to the
aid of people one has not harmed.

00:27:13.390 --> 00:27:17.400
A sin of omission can
in some circumstances,

00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:22.910
be as morally objectionable
as a sin of commission.

00:27:22.910 --> 00:27:26.370
Drawing on this conviction, the
Kew Gardens Principles developed

00:27:26.370 --> 00:27:32.960
by the Yale authors argues that an
agent has a positive responsibility

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:36.990
to help others when four
conditions are present.

00:27:36.990 --> 00:27:40.560
First, there is a critical need.

00:27:40.560 --> 00:27:45.090
Second, the agent has
proximity to the need.

00:27:45.090 --> 00:27:50.030
Third, the agent has a
capability of responding.

00:27:50.030 --> 00:27:53.820
And fourth, the agent is
likely the last resort

00:27:53.820 --> 00:27:56.750
from whom help can be expected.

00:27:56.750 --> 00:28:00.270
Subsequent reflection has
added a fifth condition,

00:28:00.270 --> 00:28:06.820
namely that the action can be
taken without disproportionate harm

00:28:06.820 --> 00:28:10.030
to the one providing help.

00:28:10.030 --> 00:28:14.090
These five criteria of course,
cannot be applied mechanically,

00:28:14.090 --> 00:28:18.630
but I think they can help
us think about the scope

00:28:18.630 --> 00:28:22.040
of our positive responsibilities
in the face

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:25.850
of the crisis level suffering
that is occurring in places

00:28:25.850 --> 00:28:29.890
like Syria and South Sudan today.

00:28:29.890 --> 00:28:35.070
For example, there can be little
doubt that grave need exists

00:28:35.070 --> 00:28:38.820
in Syria and South Sudan today.

00:28:38.820 --> 00:28:43.010
Those inside the borders of
these crisis-torn countries,

00:28:43.010 --> 00:28:47.750
are vulnerable to harms that
could lead to their deaths

00:28:47.750 --> 00:28:52.540
or to the violation of
their other basic rights.

00:28:52.540 --> 00:28:55.760
Secondly, the duty to
respond to such need,

00:28:55.760 --> 00:29:01.080
falls upon those whose proximity to
the crisis makes them more likely

00:29:01.080 --> 00:29:06.410
to have knowledge of the need,
and also better understanding

00:29:06.410 --> 00:29:08.940
of how to respond to the need.

00:29:08.940 --> 00:29:12.120
This means of course that
the government of the nation

00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:15.830
where the crisis is occurring
and the local communities

00:29:15.830 --> 00:29:19.750
within that region, bear
the prime responsibility

00:29:19.750 --> 00:29:22.420
for addressing the need involved.

00:29:22.420 --> 00:29:26.820
In South Sudan and Syria for --
therefore, both the governments

00:29:26.820 --> 00:29:31.640 position:56%
and the opposition forces in each
country, have both the negative duty

00:29:31.640 --> 00:29:35.700
to stop the atrocities they are
causing, and the positive duty

00:29:35.700 --> 00:29:40.420
to help lift the burdens the
suffering has already caused.

00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:43.280
The duty to take positive
action however,

00:29:43.280 --> 00:29:47.380
does not end at the national
borders of the countries

00:29:47.380 --> 00:29:49.940
where the crisis is present.

00:29:49.940 --> 00:29:54.360
When people become aware of a
crisis in a neighboring country,

00:29:54.360 --> 00:29:59.090
or even in a country at a great
distance, this awareness leads

00:29:59.090 --> 00:30:01.940
to what might be called
"Intellectual

00:30:01.940 --> 00:30:05.600
or Psychological Proximity."

00:30:05.600 --> 00:30:10.990
It puts people, even at a
distance in moral proximity

00:30:10.990 --> 00:30:13.320
to those who are suffering.

00:30:14.670 --> 00:30:18.070
There has been helpful,
though imperfect,

00:30:18.070 --> 00:30:23.650
response to the duties
arising from proximity

00:30:23.650 --> 00:30:27.690
by the countries neighboring
South Sudan.

00:30:27.690 --> 00:30:31.240
The regional organization of
Sudan's neighboring countries,

00:30:31.240 --> 00:30:39.270 position:56%
namely Djibouti, Ethiopia, Kenya,
Somalia, Sudan, Uganda, and Eritrea,

00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:42.600
an organization that is called
the Intergovernmental Authority

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:47.170
on Development, IGAD,
abbreviated as,

00:30:47.170 --> 00:30:51.970
IGAD has played a diplomatic role
in seeking to mediate the conflict

00:30:51.970 --> 00:30:56.320
within South Sudan,
that began in 2013,

00:30:56.320 --> 00:30:59.070
as it did during the earlier effort

00:30:59.070 --> 00:31:02.470
to bring the comprehensive
peace agreement to Sudan

00:31:02.470 --> 00:31:06.310
that ended the conflict between
Northern and Southern Sudan,

00:31:06.310 --> 00:31:10.310
that ultimately led to the
independence of South Sudan.

00:31:10.310 --> 00:31:14.340
Regrettably, the economic
and political self-interest

00:31:14.340 --> 00:31:20.170
of these countries in IGAD has
sometimes distorted their mediation

00:31:20.170 --> 00:31:25.150
efforts, leading particularly
of Uganda and Ethiopia,

00:31:25.150 --> 00:31:27.840
which has in turn led
several countries

00:31:27.840 --> 00:31:32.490
at even greater distances outside
the region to become involved

00:31:32.490 --> 00:31:35.730
in mediating the diplomatic
efforts to bring an end

00:31:35.730 --> 00:31:41.060
to the South Sudan crisis, through
an initiative called IGAD Plus,

00:31:41.060 --> 00:31:44.350
which includes not only
South Sudan's neighbors,

00:31:44.350 --> 00:31:48.660
but also the African Union, the
United Nations, China, the U.S.,

00:31:48.660 --> 00:31:52.060
the United Kingdom, Norway,
and the European Union.

00:31:52.060 --> 00:31:55.830
A sense of moral responsibility
arose

00:31:55.830 --> 00:31:58.430
in these more distant countries,

00:31:58.430 --> 00:32:02.540
because of their proximity
through awareness.

00:32:02.540 --> 00:32:05.050
What I'm calling, moral proximity.

00:32:05.050 --> 00:32:09.690
These combined regional and global
mediation efforts have been far

00:32:09.690 --> 00:32:12.180
from perfect to be sure.

00:32:12.180 --> 00:32:19.530
However, a fragile peace process
is underway and there's even a sign

00:32:19.530 --> 00:32:24.130
of hope that it may be
leading to a positive outcome.

00:32:24.130 --> 00:32:29.080
Even today, new news of Riek
Machar returning back to Juba

00:32:29.080 --> 00:32:32.940
with the possibility of moving
in back into the government

00:32:32.940 --> 00:32:35.030
to heal some of the
wounds that are there.

00:32:35.030 --> 00:32:38.080
At least there's a hope
that this could happen.

00:32:38.080 --> 00:32:39.460
And it points to the fact

00:32:39.460 --> 00:32:42.560
that distant neighbors
can make a difference

00:32:42.560 --> 00:32:45.430
in addressing these crises.

00:32:45.430 --> 00:32:49.980
The criterion of capability also
sheds light on the positive duties

00:32:49.980 --> 00:32:52.900
to respond to humanity in crisis.

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:56.760
In considering this issue,
it has become common to point

00:32:56.760 --> 00:33:01.350
out that someone who cannot swim,
does not have a duty to come

00:33:01.350 --> 00:33:07.010
to the aid of a child who is
drowning a rapidly flowing river,

00:33:07.010 --> 00:33:10.380
if aid requires swimming
some distance

00:33:10.380 --> 00:33:13.930
that the person is incapable of.

00:33:13.930 --> 00:33:19.080 position:56%
On the other hand, a good swimmer,
could have a duty to come to the aid

00:33:19.080 --> 00:33:22.520
of such a child in the river.

00:33:22.520 --> 00:33:25.130
Lebanon, Turkey, and Jordan,

00:33:25.130 --> 00:33:31.510 position:56%
are already massively
overburdened by the Syrian refugees.

00:33:31.510 --> 00:33:35.960
In my judgement, they do not
possess the economic resources

00:33:35.960 --> 00:33:42.240
to provide asylum for additional
refugees in the current situation.

00:33:42.240 --> 00:33:45.220
On the other hand, the resources
of the wealthy countries

00:33:45.220 --> 00:33:50.730
of Northern Europe, North America,
and the oil producing Gulf states,

00:33:50.730 --> 00:33:55.420
gives them the capability to
receive many more asylum seekers

00:33:55.420 --> 00:33:59.760
than they are, and to share
the burdens being carried

00:33:59.760 --> 00:34:03.300
by Syria's already
overburdened neighbors,

00:34:03.300 --> 00:34:08.660
by providing financial assistance,
to those surrounding neighbors.

00:34:08.660 --> 00:34:13.290
The assistance being provided to
the countries bordering on Syria,

00:34:13.290 --> 00:34:17.410
financial, is woefully inadequate.

00:34:17.410 --> 00:34:21.110
Our capability it seems
to me, gives us a duty,

00:34:21.110 --> 00:34:26.830 position:56%
both to receive more Syrian refugees
than we have, and especially

00:34:26.830 --> 00:34:33.220 position:56%
to do much more to provide direct
financial assistance and other forms

00:34:33.220 --> 00:34:38.710
of technological and humanitarian
aid to help Syria's near neighbors,

00:34:38.710 --> 00:34:43.860
deal with the massive number of
refugees they are dealing with.

00:34:43.860 --> 00:34:50.210
The responsibility of the Doctrine
of the Responsibility to Protect,

00:34:50.210 --> 00:34:53.940
that was affirmed at the
2005 General Assembly

00:34:53.940 --> 00:34:57.780 position:56%
of the World's Summit -- General
Assembly of the U.N.'s World Summit,

00:34:57.780 --> 00:35:00.640
states that the international
community can have --

00:35:00.640 --> 00:35:06.350
do positive duties to help
protect populations from genocide,

00:35:06.350 --> 00:35:10.910
war crimes, ethnic cleansing,
and crimes against humanity.

00:35:10.910 --> 00:35:16.310
Such crimes are clearly occurring
in Syria and South Sudan today.

00:35:16.310 --> 00:35:20.710
In the first instance, such
protective efforts should be

00:35:20.710 --> 00:35:24.560
through diplomatic, humanitarian
and peaceful meanings.

00:35:24.560 --> 00:35:27.930
But if such peaceful initiatives
do not succeed however,

00:35:27.930 --> 00:35:33.470 position:56%
the use of armed force can become a
legitimate way to carry out the duty

00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:37.330
to protect people from
violations of their rights

00:35:37.330 --> 00:35:40.910
that reach the level of atrocity.

00:35:40.910 --> 00:35:44.510
The responsibility to
protect doctrine of course,

00:35:44.510 --> 00:35:48.620
has been the focus of much
controversy, heated controversy,

00:35:48.620 --> 00:35:53.360
since it was first
proclaimed by the U.N. in 2005.

00:35:53.360 --> 00:35:56.740
Political realists oppose
it because they hold

00:35:56.740 --> 00:36:00.480
that foreign policy should be
determined by the interests

00:36:00.480 --> 00:36:02.510
of one's own people, not

00:36:02.510 --> 00:36:07.690
by a supposed moral
responsibility to other lands.

00:36:07.690 --> 00:36:10.540
Others see the responsibility
to protect,

00:36:10.540 --> 00:36:18.730
as a form of neo-imperialism, an
expansion of what the French used

00:36:18.730 --> 00:36:24.440
to call the advancement
of civilization.

00:36:24.440 --> 00:36:27.960
Still others say that
what happened in Libya,

00:36:27.960 --> 00:36:31.980
shows that that the responsibility
to protect doesn't work.

00:36:31.980 --> 00:36:37.190
And that what's happening in Syria
today shows that it can't work.

00:36:37.190 --> 00:36:41.090
Despite these critiques,
it is important to note

00:36:41.090 --> 00:36:45.280
that the responsibility to protect
has been invoked on a number

00:36:45.280 --> 00:36:50.880
of occasions since 2005,
and that it has in fact led

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:53.360
to the effective protection
of people

00:36:53.360 --> 00:36:55.650
from grave human rights violations.

00:36:55.650 --> 00:36:59.900
For example, when conflict
flared in Kenya,

00:36:59.900 --> 00:37:05.180
following the disputed 2007
elections, Kofi Annan said

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:08.680
that he looked at the
crisis through the prism

00:37:08.680 --> 00:37:11.740
of the responsibility to protect.

00:37:11.740 --> 00:37:16.560
This led him to initiate and
to stimulate others to follow,

00:37:16.560 --> 00:37:22.850 position:56%
in creating diplomatic interventions
by the U.N., the African Union,

00:37:22.850 --> 00:37:26.680
a number of other governments
from Africa and around the world,

00:37:26.680 --> 00:37:29.400
including the United States.

00:37:29.400 --> 00:37:33.460 position:56%
Condoleezza Rice went there
herself to try to mediate the crisis

00:37:33.460 --> 00:37:36.490
in Kenya following the election.

00:37:36.490 --> 00:37:42.030
A power sharing agreement was
reached between the two forces

00:37:42.030 --> 00:37:49.330
that were adversaries in Kenya, and
the downward spiral into civil war

00:37:49.330 --> 00:37:52.670
and what some feared was
moving toward genocide was

00:37:52.670 --> 00:37:54.770
actually stopped.

00:37:54.770 --> 00:37:59.090
The Kenyan case illustrates in my
judgement, that the responsibility

00:37:59.090 --> 00:38:03.140
to protect can be successfully
carried out through nonviolent,

00:38:03.140 --> 00:38:06.110
political and diplomatic
initiatives.

00:38:06.110 --> 00:38:10.570
The responsibility to protect
doctrine has also been invoked

00:38:10.570 --> 00:38:14.780
on several occasions in the
past decade, to justify the use

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:20.110
of military force to protect
people from grave atrocities.

00:38:20.110 --> 00:38:24.780
In 2012, with the U.N.
Security Council approval,

00:38:24.780 --> 00:38:29.790
France and the economic
community of West African states,

00:38:29.790 --> 00:38:35.170
took military action in
pursuit of peace in Mali.

00:38:35.170 --> 00:38:43.220 position:56%
And in 2013, the Security Council
supported the use of force by France

00:38:43.220 --> 00:38:46.780
and the African Union
to stop atrocities

00:38:46.780 --> 00:38:50.280
in the Central Africa Republic.

00:38:50.280 --> 00:38:57.580
These cases, Mali and CAR, Central
African Republic, indicate to me

00:38:57.580 --> 00:39:03.460
that the responsibility to
protect can remain a viable option

00:39:03.460 --> 00:39:05.890
in grave crisis.

00:39:05.890 --> 00:39:09.390
Two other cases however,
Libya and Syria,

00:39:09.390 --> 00:39:13.120
cause others to question this.

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:15.920
In the Libya case, the
U.N. authorized action

00:39:15.920 --> 00:39:20.870
to protect civilians when
fears arose that Gaddafi was

00:39:20.870 --> 00:39:23.700
about to commit atrocities.

00:39:23.700 --> 00:39:26.790
He had done a lot of bad things
already, but there was fear

00:39:26.790 --> 00:39:29.230
that he was even going
to do worse things.

00:39:29.230 --> 00:39:32.610
For example, when he
referred to his adversaries

00:39:32.610 --> 00:39:37.520
in Benghazi as "cockroaches."

00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:41.210
This is the very epithet
that the Hutus used

00:39:41.210 --> 00:39:46.600
of the Tutsi during the
midst of the Rwanda genocide.

00:39:46.600 --> 00:39:51.630
And it led a number of people to
think that Gaddafi was on the verge

00:39:51.630 --> 00:39:54.450
of an extermination
of his adversaries.

00:39:54.450 --> 00:40:00.810
As a result, the Security
Council with the notable support

00:40:00.810 --> 00:40:05.410
of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference, and the League

00:40:05.410 --> 00:40:08.470
of Arab States, called
for the use of quote,

00:40:08.470 --> 00:40:12.730
"All necessary measures
to protect civilians."

00:40:12.730 --> 00:40:15.470
NATO intervened with air power.

00:40:15.470 --> 00:40:20.020
Gaddafi was killed and
his regime was overthrown.

00:40:20.020 --> 00:40:26.020
Sadly, and this is what leads the
critics to say RtoP doesn't work,

00:40:26.020 --> 00:40:29.330
Libya has fallen into
political chaos,

00:40:29.330 --> 00:40:33.860
with armed conflicts among several
groups, significant violations

00:40:33.860 --> 00:40:37.670
of human rights continuing
on the basis of religion,

00:40:37.670 --> 00:40:42.960 position:56%
and the unsafe flight of migrants
across the Mediterranean from Libya.

00:40:42.960 --> 00:40:46.310
These consequences confirm
some in the conviction

00:40:46.310 --> 00:40:48.470
that pursuing humanitarian goals,

00:40:48.470 --> 00:40:51.240
not required by national
self-interest,

00:40:51.240 --> 00:40:54.570 position:56%
is likely to do more harm than good.

00:40:54.570 --> 00:41:00.220
I would argue however, that the
intervention in Libya failed,

00:41:00.220 --> 00:41:05.630
not because it was excessive,
but because it was incomplete.

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:10.280
Following the norms that my
colleagues in ethics today call

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:16.290
"jus post bellum,"
justice following conflict,

00:41:16.290 --> 00:41:20.060
NATO and the U.S. should have
followed up their intervention

00:41:20.060 --> 00:41:27.030
with action to rebuild Libya and to
prevent the chaos that developed.

00:41:27.030 --> 00:41:30.230
What happened in Libya
was in my judgement,

00:41:30.230 --> 00:41:34.810
an incomplete implementation
of the responsibility

00:41:34.810 --> 00:41:38.670
to protect, not a simple failure.

00:41:38.670 --> 00:41:41.380
Syria has also been
invoked to suggest

00:41:41.380 --> 00:41:45.310
that the responsibility
to protect is dead.

00:41:45.310 --> 00:41:48.780
The political complexities
and moral ambiguities

00:41:48.780 --> 00:41:53.010
of the Syrian situation,
surely go very deep.

00:41:53.010 --> 00:41:57.750
But these complexities in my
view, do not discredit the notion

00:41:57.750 --> 00:42:00.830
of the responsibility to protect.

00:42:00.830 --> 00:42:05.890 position:56%
Thomas Weiss has argued that the
"wisdom of the use of military force

00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:13.200 position:56%
to protect people from atrocities is
governed by three factors: legality,

00:42:13.200 --> 00:42:17.100
moral legitimacy, and feasibility."

00:42:17.100 --> 00:42:22.720
In Syria, it is clear that the
legal prohibitions of war crimes

00:42:22.720 --> 00:42:26.910
and of other atrocities,
have been violated.

00:42:26.910 --> 00:42:31.950
The moral legitimacy of efforts to
stop a conflict that has displaced

00:42:31.950 --> 00:42:36.510
over half the entire Syrian
population, and killed hundreds

00:42:36.510 --> 00:42:40.290
of thousands of Syrians,
is also evident.

00:42:40.290 --> 00:42:43.950
The issue of course is feasibility.

00:42:43.950 --> 00:42:48.680 position:56%
Feasibility of military intervention
to alleviate the crisis,

00:42:48.680 --> 00:42:53.260
and this I think is -- this
feasibility is unclear.

00:42:53.260 --> 00:42:57.080
This does not undermine the idea
that there is a responsibility

00:42:57.080 --> 00:43:00.770
to protect people from atrocity.

00:43:00.770 --> 00:43:05.380
The apparent lack of a presently
feasible way to overcome the crisis

00:43:05.380 --> 00:43:10.490
in Syria I would argue, calls
for additional political

00:43:10.490 --> 00:43:14.780
and diplomatic initiatives
to find a path forward.

00:43:14.780 --> 00:43:24.890
Not only Assad and the rebels, but
also Russia, Iran, the Gulf states,

00:43:24.890 --> 00:43:29.660
and some others, are keeping
the crisis in Syria alive.

00:43:29.660 --> 00:43:35.280
The United States has a duty, in my
judgement, to engage these powers

00:43:35.280 --> 00:43:39.410
in the pursuit of peace,
through continuing political

00:43:39.410 --> 00:43:41.040
and diplomatic engagement.

00:43:41.040 --> 00:43:47.280
In my judgement, Secretary
Kerry is on the right path here.

00:43:47.280 --> 00:43:52.380 position:56%
Outside of Syria itself, what is our
responsibility to the large number

00:43:52.380 --> 00:43:56.320
of Syrians presently
seeking asylum in Europe,

00:43:56.320 --> 00:43:59.200
and other parts of
the developed world?

00:43:59.200 --> 00:44:04.280
We should affirm -- we should
reaffirm the United Nations 1951

00:44:04.280 --> 00:44:09.470
Refugee Conventions Affirmation
that refugees fleeing persecution,

00:44:09.470 --> 00:44:13.050
should be granted asylum elsewhere.

00:44:13.050 --> 00:44:17.300
Countries in Europe and North
America have the capability

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:22.050
and the resources to grant asylum
to a considerably larger number

00:44:22.050 --> 00:44:27.310
of refugees from Syria and South
Sudan than we are doing today.

00:44:27.310 --> 00:44:31.530
Indeed, the number of Syrians
seeking asylum in Europe,

00:44:31.530 --> 00:44:34.740
is not even close to
the number already

00:44:34.740 --> 00:44:38.490
within the borders
of Syria's neighbors.

00:44:38.490 --> 00:44:41.820
For example, in the
fall of last year,

00:44:41.820 --> 00:44:46.030
when Prime Minister David Cameron
of the United Kingdom announced

00:44:46.030 --> 00:44:51.630
that is country would grant
asylum to 20,000 Syrian refugees

00:44:51.630 --> 00:44:57.030
over the next 5 years, he
was appropriately reminded

00:44:57.030 --> 00:45:02.260
that Lebanon had admitted
that number of Syrian refugees

00:45:02.260 --> 00:45:05.170
over the last two weekends.

00:45:06.800 --> 00:45:13.890
Indeed, developing
countries today host 86%

00:45:13.890 --> 00:45:17.410
of all the world's refugees.

00:45:17.410 --> 00:45:22.430
And the very poorest countries of
the world, are providing asylum

00:45:22.430 --> 00:45:27.750
to 25% of the global
total of refugees.

00:45:27.750 --> 00:45:32.920
The rich nations of the north,
like us, have the capability

00:45:32.920 --> 00:45:38.150
and therefore the responsibility
to admit a larger number

00:45:38.150 --> 00:45:41.800
of asylum seekers, and
even more I would say

00:45:41.800 --> 00:45:44.610
to assist these poorer countries

00:45:44.610 --> 00:45:51.020
who are already hosting most
of the world's refugees.

00:45:51.020 --> 00:45:56.240
The funds being provided for this
burden sharing by us in the north,

00:45:56.240 --> 00:45:59.700
need to be substantially increased.

00:45:59.700 --> 00:46:03.210
To achieve this, the rich nations
of the northern hemisphere,

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:08.040
will have to overcome
tendencies to racially

00:46:08.040 --> 00:46:13.690
and religiously driven xenophobia,
and overcome the mistaken fear

00:46:13.690 --> 00:46:18.600
that most terrorists
have come in as refugees.

00:46:18.600 --> 00:46:22.800
Most terrorists are actually
native born people, born within --

00:46:22.800 --> 00:46:27.490
the French terrorists who blew
up the -- took action in Paris,

00:46:27.490 --> 00:46:28.790
and those who took action

00:46:28.790 --> 00:46:31.970
in Brussels were all born
in France and Belgium.

00:46:31.970 --> 00:46:35.630
A country with a history
of military involvement

00:46:35.630 --> 00:46:39.160
in another country can also
have special obligations.

00:46:39.160 --> 00:46:43.570
For example, the United States
recognized its particular duty

00:46:43.570 --> 00:46:48.150
to receive refugees from
Vietnam, after the Vietnam war.

00:46:48.150 --> 00:46:54.100 position:56%
Though the U.S. intervention in Iraq
was certainly not the sole course --

00:46:54.100 --> 00:46:58.820
cause of displacement of many
Iraqis in the world today,

00:46:58.820 --> 00:47:01.570
it was surely the occasion

00:47:01.570 --> 00:47:06.150
of the huge forced migration
of Iraqis that followed.

00:47:06.150 --> 00:47:09.470
And political scientist
Steven Walt recently observed

00:47:09.470 --> 00:47:13.520
in a somewhat cynical column,
that if the United States

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:19.310
and its allies had not invaded Iraq
in 2003, there would almost no --

00:47:19.310 --> 00:47:22.920 position:56%
certainly be no Islamic state today,

00:47:22.920 --> 00:47:24.880
which would then be
raising questions

00:47:24.880 --> 00:47:28.220
about our duty toward the
people being displaced

00:47:28.220 --> 00:47:31.620
by the Islamic state.

00:47:31.620 --> 00:47:34.130
If we had not intervened,
it seems to me,

00:47:34.130 --> 00:47:37.580
there would surely be
fewer people seeking asylum

00:47:37.580 --> 00:47:40.830
from Iraq and Syria today.

00:47:40.830 --> 00:47:45.300
This deepens our duties toward
those refugees, in my judgment.

00:47:45.300 --> 00:47:48.450
Finally, I recognize
that there are reasons

00:47:48.450 --> 00:47:53.990 position:56%
to wonder whether national
self-interest will not almost always

00:47:53.990 --> 00:47:58.150
overshadow the duties
that I've been sketching

00:47:58.150 --> 00:48:01.050
and that I then advocating.

00:48:01.050 --> 00:48:06.350
Nevertheless, I am encouraged by
the recent work of Martha Finnemore

00:48:06.350 --> 00:48:11.360
and Kathryn Sikkink, two
distinguished political scientists,

00:48:11.360 --> 00:48:17.820 position:56%
whose work shows the positive impact
of people who have been advocating

00:48:17.820 --> 00:48:22.800
for normative, ethical
standards in some domains

00:48:22.800 --> 00:48:26.080
of contemporary international
politics.

00:48:26.080 --> 00:48:30.600
The standards of international law
of armed conflict, where the result

00:48:30.600 --> 00:48:37.650
of normative advocacy, by
groups such as the Red Cross

00:48:37.650 --> 00:48:41.090
over the past century,
leading to the creation

00:48:41.090 --> 00:48:43.470
of the Geneva Conventions.

00:48:43.470 --> 00:48:46.810
More recently, though the
International Criminal Court is

00:48:46.810 --> 00:48:52.870
still by all means, a
developing institution, Finnemore

00:48:52.870 --> 00:48:57.190
and Sikkink have argued that,
"normative entrepreneurs,"

00:48:57.190 --> 00:49:00.180
as they call them, have
advanced the effort

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:06.510
to hold political leaders
accountable for violating standards

00:49:06.510 --> 00:49:09.610
through the action of several
international criminal tribunals.

00:49:09.610 --> 00:49:12.080
Not only the International
Criminal Court,

00:49:12.080 --> 00:49:14.440
but the International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda,

00:49:14.440 --> 00:49:18.540 position:56%
the International Criminal Tribunal
for the former Yugoslavia, etcetera.

00:49:18.540 --> 00:49:23.140
This suggests that contrary to
the standard realist argument,

00:49:23.140 --> 00:49:27.830
ethical standards can
come to have real impact

00:49:27.830 --> 00:49:30.050
on the conduct of nations.

00:49:30.050 --> 00:49:37.130
My hope is that strong ethical
pressure, including pressure

00:49:37.130 --> 00:49:42.150
from faith-based agencies like
the pressure we saw from the Pope

00:49:42.150 --> 00:49:44.030
in Lesbos, just a few day --

00:49:44.030 --> 00:49:50.050
few weeks ago, that this pressure
will lead to more action in accord

00:49:50.050 --> 00:49:51.550
with the responsibilities

00:49:51.550 --> 00:49:54.340
that I have incompletely
sketched here today.

00:49:54.340 --> 00:49:58.280
And that I hope to treat in
considerably greater depth

00:49:58.280 --> 00:50:03.130 position:56%
in the book that I'm writing, thanks
to my stay at the Kluge Center.

00:50:03.130 --> 00:50:04.930
Thank you.

