case, you know and the Rwanda case,

00:54:54.220 --> 00:54:57.530
as awful as the humanitarian
issue was,

00:54:57.530 --> 00:55:00.110
some people would say it was a
stretch to say that interests were

00:55:00.110 --> 00:55:02.830
at stake, even though you
and I might agree they were.

00:55:02.830 --> 00:55:04.640
But here in Syria,
we have a situation

00:55:04.640 --> 00:55:10.740 position:56%
where the awful humanitarian
situation has impacted, as you said,

00:55:10.740 --> 00:55:13.630
the stability of many
states in the region.

00:55:13.630 --> 00:55:14.930
&gt;&gt; Dr. David Hollenbach:
Even the E.U.

00:55:14.930 --> 00:55:16.940 position:56%
&gt;&gt; And that of course to Europe now.

00:55:16.940 --> 00:55:18.980
And so anybody who would
say, "Well, you know,

00:55:18.980 --> 00:55:20.770
that's a really terrible thing.

00:55:20.770 --> 00:55:24.680
It's just about you know,
values," could there possibly be

00:55:24.680 --> 00:55:27.950
and maybe a way towards the end of
your book to say that these really,

00:55:27.950 --> 00:55:30.820
in a globalized, interconnected
world, that the dichotomy

00:55:30.820 --> 00:55:35.850 position:56%
between interests and ideals, really
holds up less, and there's more

00:55:35.850 --> 00:55:39.150
of a kind of cross-connection
between them?

00:55:39.150 --> 00:55:41.270
&gt;&gt; Dr. David Hollenbach:
I fully agree with that.

00:55:41.270 --> 00:55:45.310
I certainly don't want to make
it as if the whole response

00:55:45.310 --> 00:55:48.070
to my argument today
is all about ethics

00:55:48.070 --> 00:55:50.060
and self-interest has
nothing to do with it.

00:55:50.060 --> 00:55:53.310
I do think that there are
real self-interests involved.

00:55:53.310 --> 00:55:55.280
I mean, it's not only
what's happening.

00:55:55.280 --> 00:56:01.210
I mean, if this crisis with
the Syrian refugees leads

00:56:01.210 --> 00:56:04.150
to the disintegration
of the European Union,

00:56:04.150 --> 00:56:07.080
I mean that's really
serious business.

00:56:07.080 --> 00:56:10.160
I mean the European Union has
been the source of peace in Europe

00:56:10.160 --> 00:56:13.960
for the last -- since
the Second World War,

00:56:13.960 --> 00:56:17.070
or the Union more recently.

00:56:17.070 --> 00:56:21.630
But we don't want to repeat
World War I and World War II,

00:56:21.630 --> 00:56:23.670
and finding ways to prevent that is

00:56:23.670 --> 00:56:25.980
in our self-interest,
it seems to me.

00:56:25.980 --> 00:56:29.730
Now that's not the only
self-interested people.

00:56:29.730 --> 00:56:32.910
The response to the whole
Middle Eastern situation,

00:56:32.910 --> 00:56:36.140
if this Syria crisis
flows over and --

00:56:36.140 --> 00:56:39.030
into other regions of
the Middle East, if --

00:56:39.030 --> 00:56:42.420
especially if we weren't producing
cheap oil the way we are right now

00:56:42.420 --> 00:56:45.520
because of fracking, which
raises another whole question,

00:56:45.520 --> 00:56:47.960
but we'll deal with
fracking another day.

00:56:47.960 --> 00:56:51.320
But there is a self-interest
involved

00:56:51.320 --> 00:56:53.360
in keeping peace in these regions.

00:56:53.360 --> 00:56:55.440
And that means responding
to these crises.

00:56:55.440 --> 00:56:58.050
So I think they go together.

00:56:58.050 --> 00:57:02.720
The other thing is that from
a normative point of view,

00:57:02.720 --> 00:57:06.340
this probably comes from
Catholic background rather

00:57:06.340 --> 00:57:10.640
than from another approach,
I'm not entirely sure

00:57:10.640 --> 00:57:16.110
that drawing a sharp
distinction between self-interest

00:57:16.110 --> 00:57:19.840
and purely altruistic
other interest,

00:57:19.840 --> 00:57:24.850
is a legitimate way
to think about ethics.

00:57:24.850 --> 00:57:30.900
I think my well-being and
other's well-being are inherently

00:57:30.900 --> 00:57:32.780
interconnected with each other.

00:57:32.780 --> 00:57:35.810
That goes back to Aristotle,
talking about the fact

00:57:35.810 --> 00:57:38.630
that a human being
is a social being.

00:57:38.630 --> 00:57:43.460
We are interdependent on each
other, throughout our whole lives.

00:57:43.460 --> 00:57:49.660
So to think of a pure self-interest
that's totally dissociated

00:57:49.660 --> 00:57:52.940
from any concern for others,
doesn't make sense in terms

00:57:52.940 --> 00:57:54.690
of the kind of being we are.

00:57:54.690 --> 00:57:58.410
We're not little atoms,
separated from each other.

00:57:58.410 --> 00:58:02.730
And the growing globalization
and interdependence economically

00:58:02.730 --> 00:58:07.190
and culturally and politically
makes that even more obvious today,

00:58:07.190 --> 00:58:08.920
than it would have
been some time ago.

00:58:08.920 --> 00:58:11.950
So I'm very much in
agreement with your direction.

00:58:11.950 --> 00:58:13.910
Yes?

00:58:13.910 --> 00:58:15.210
&gt;&gt; Hello, David.

00:58:15.210 --> 00:58:16.510
I'm Jim Lund [phonetic].

00:58:16.510 --> 00:58:17.810
I'm now with [inaudible].

00:58:17.810 --> 00:58:19.110
&gt;&gt; Dr. David Hollenbach: Hi, Jim.

00:58:19.110 --> 00:58:20.410
Good to see you.

00:58:20.410 --> 00:58:21.710
&gt;&gt; Good to see you.

00:58:21.710 --> 00:58:23.180
Let me just say that the first time
I heard you lecture was in 1977.

00:58:23.180 --> 00:58:25.710
And I still remember what you said.

00:58:25.710 --> 00:58:27.140
&gt;&gt; Dr. David Hollenbach:
Well, that's amazing.

00:58:27.140 --> 00:58:29.170
I don't.

00:58:29.170 --> 00:58:31.970
&gt;&gt; And so I thought I'd wander up
Capitol Hill to hear you today.

00:58:31.970 --> 00:58:35.760
So thank you very much for your
insights and wisdom here today.

00:58:35.760 --> 00:58:38.050
I didn't hear you talk
much about last resort.

00:58:38.050 --> 00:58:40.850
Now, I think the situation
in South Sudan,

00:58:40.850 --> 00:58:44.680 position:56%
the situation in Syria is
self-evidently, we're in a situation

00:58:44.680 --> 00:58:47.650
of last resort with the millions
of people that are affected.

00:58:47.650 --> 00:58:49.500
But could you talk a
little bit about that

00:58:49.500 --> 00:58:52.260
from a philosophical framework too?

00:58:52.260 --> 00:58:54.300
&gt;&gt; Dr. David Hollenbach: Well,
I think that probably touches

00:58:54.300 --> 00:59:00.250
on what Tom Weiss calls
"feasibility" also.

00:59:03.760 --> 00:59:08.870
Certainly, last resort is invoked
in the Just War Tradition to say,

00:59:08.870 --> 00:59:11.720
you don't start using force

00:59:11.720 --> 00:59:14.210
if you could take another
initiative diplomatically

00:59:14.210 --> 00:59:17.410
that would solve the problem
without the use of armed force.

00:59:17.410 --> 00:59:21.190
I mean it follows from
the fact that the use

00:59:21.190 --> 00:59:24.720
of armed force involves
killing people.

00:59:24.720 --> 00:59:28.550
And you don't do that if you really
take seriously the Thou Shalt Not

00:59:28.550 --> 00:59:36.150
Kill commandment, unless it's the
only way to protect innocent people

00:59:36.150 --> 00:59:39.970
from being killed, and that means
last resort comes into play there.

00:59:39.970 --> 00:59:46.680
So finding steps that would take
action to -- I mentioned Kenya.

00:59:46.680 --> 00:59:51.720 position:56%
Kenya is an example of a diplomatic
implementation of the responsibility

00:59:51.720 --> 00:59:56.700
to protect that did not
involve the use of armed force.

00:59:56.700 --> 00:59:59.500
Following the election there,
it looked like Kenya was going

00:59:59.500 --> 01:00:03.250
to fall apart into an ethnic war.

01:00:03.250 --> 01:00:07.460
The major ethnic groups of Kenya
have been divided for a long time.

01:00:07.460 --> 01:00:10.890
It felt very much like
-- it looked like that,

01:00:10.890 --> 01:00:15.700
and that's why there was a sense
that we've got to do something

01:00:15.700 --> 01:00:17.990
to prevent another Rwanda.

01:00:17.990 --> 01:00:20.560
That was Kofi Annan's position.

01:00:20.560 --> 01:00:23.260 position:56%
And Kofi Annan had been the Director

01:00:23.260 --> 01:00:26.490
of Peacekeeping Operations
during the Rwanda genocide,

01:00:26.490 --> 01:00:30.430
which led him to be very sensitive
to this, because he had failed

01:00:30.430 --> 01:00:34.760
to take the action needed in Rwanda
to prevent what happened there.

01:00:34.760 --> 01:00:39.420
So, he took action, but it
was not military action.

01:00:39.420 --> 01:00:43.050
And I think to say, that's
a good example of the use

01:00:43.050 --> 01:00:47.150
of force should be only in the
last resort, if you can find ways

01:00:47.150 --> 01:00:50.870
to take those diplomatic maneuvers
that will solve the problem

01:00:50.870 --> 01:00:52.980
and protect people, do it.

01:00:52.980 --> 01:00:54.960
Don't intervene militarily.

01:00:54.960 --> 01:00:59.640 position:56%
Now, in Syria, I think we've
probably reached the point of saying

01:00:59.640 --> 01:01:07.110
that if we could militarily
intervene, and do so,

01:01:07.110 --> 01:01:08.820
there's another criterion

01:01:08.820 --> 01:01:14.360
of Just War Theory called
Reasonable Hope of Success.

01:01:14.360 --> 01:01:16.180
You don't want to intervene
militarily

01:01:16.180 --> 01:01:17.870
if you don't have a good
hope that it's going

01:01:17.870 --> 01:01:20.500
to make the situation better.

01:01:20.500 --> 01:01:23.690
The fear is that a military
intervention by the United States

01:01:23.690 --> 01:01:27.440
in Syria today would
make the situation worse.

01:01:27.440 --> 01:01:31.210
And that's where I think, last
resort, as well as Reasonable Hope

01:01:31.210 --> 01:01:35.640 position:56%
of Success may point to saying,
we've got to take other steps to try

01:01:35.640 --> 01:01:37.840
to move in a new direction.

01:01:37.840 --> 01:01:39.760
I don't know what those are.

01:01:39.760 --> 01:01:42.830
I know Secretary Kerry has
been really working hard on it,

01:01:42.830 --> 01:01:46.300
and he's taken some steps that
have moved in the right direction,

01:01:46.300 --> 01:01:48.830
but we're way far removed
from where we are.

01:01:48.830 --> 01:01:53.820 position:56%
I do think our remaining obligation
is to make sure we do something more

01:01:53.820 --> 01:01:56.920
to help all these people
who are being displaced.

01:01:56.920 --> 01:01:59.190
These millions of Syrian refugees.

01:01:59.190 --> 01:02:02.300
Anyway, I'm just thinking
out loud about this.

01:02:02.300 --> 01:02:03.910
I'm not answering the question,

01:02:03.910 --> 01:02:08.050
because I don't think there's a
clear answer to the Syrian question

01:02:08.050 --> 01:02:09.350
that sound -- that looks

01:02:09.350 --> 01:02:13.770
so perfectly beautiful
and solves the problem.

01:02:13.770 --> 01:02:15.070
Yes, sir?

01:02:15.070 --> 01:02:23.280
&gt;&gt; I want to compliment you
on a brilliant talk first.

01:02:23.280 --> 01:02:24.630
&gt;&gt; Dr. David Hollenbach:
Oh well, thank you so much.

01:02:24.630 --> 01:02:25.960
I'm very grateful.

01:02:25.960 --> 01:02:29.770
&gt;&gt; But I also want to
introduce a new thought here.

01:02:30.820 --> 01:02:37.860
My slogan for 2016-17 is that
we cannot afford war any longer.

01:02:37.860 --> 01:02:41.990
Now just think about that.

01:02:41.990 --> 01:02:47.800
Every country in the world
seems to be consumed with debt,

01:02:47.800 --> 01:02:53.730
consumed with other projects that
are worthwhile, so I want to think

01:02:53.730 --> 01:02:58.850
about the thought, well we
can't afford war anymore.

01:02:58.850 --> 01:03:02.710
And it's a Catholic idea
that all need each other.

01:03:02.710 --> 01:03:06.340
Now I'm in the oil business,
so I know what the price

01:03:06.340 --> 01:03:11.880
of oil dropping is, but I also
think it's good for the world too.

01:03:11.880 --> 01:03:19.330 position:56%
And so -- but on the other hand, the
last time Reagan dropped the price

01:03:19.330 --> 01:03:22.630
of oil in a war with the Saudi --

01:03:22.630 --> 01:03:29.490
the Russians, 3,000 independent
oil companies went out of business.

01:03:29.490 --> 01:03:32.210
I used to be a bank
director and I will predict,

01:03:32.210 --> 01:03:34.590
a lot of oil companies,
small oil companies,

01:03:34.590 --> 01:03:37.240
will go out of business again.

01:03:37.240 --> 01:03:44.400
Now, what's that got to
do with the price of eggs?

01:03:44.400 --> 01:03:50.370
I say that if we can't
afford war anymore,

01:03:50.370 --> 01:03:53.150
then we ought to be
talking about that.

01:03:53.150 --> 01:03:56.610
And from a religious point
of view, we've been talking

01:03:56.610 --> 01:03:57.930
about that for centuries.

01:03:57.930 --> 01:04:02.150
So, just want to throw
that out as a thought.

01:04:02.150 --> 01:04:03.520
Thank you.

01:04:03.520 --> 01:04:04.820
&gt;&gt; Dr. David Hollenbach:
Thank you very much

01:04:04.820 --> 01:04:13.330
and I'm certainly very much in
agreement with finding alternatives

01:04:13.330 --> 01:04:18.640
to war is a very, extremely
important step.

01:04:18.640 --> 01:04:23.530
I've been challenged by some of
my colleagues in the ethics area

01:04:23.530 --> 01:04:27.740
for saying that I still
hold the possibility

01:04:27.740 --> 01:04:30.040
of some legitimate
use of armed force.

01:04:30.040 --> 01:04:35.080
Some people want to say it's
totally unacceptable today.

01:04:35.080 --> 01:04:38.620
The only thing that
has led me to not move

01:04:38.620 --> 01:04:42.040
in that direction is having
spent some time in Rwanda

01:04:42.040 --> 01:04:47.270
and having seen the aftermath
of what happened there,

01:04:47.270 --> 01:04:49.940
which could have been prevented.

01:04:49.940 --> 01:04:53.810
General Romeo Dallaire who was
the Canadian General in charge

01:04:53.810 --> 01:04:56.160
of the Rwandan peacekeeping troops,

01:04:56.160 --> 01:04:59.780
said that if he had had 5,000
more peacekeeping troops,

01:04:59.780 --> 01:05:04.520
he could have saved 300,000 lives.

01:05:04.520 --> 01:05:09.270
Well, that use of armed force, I'm
in favor of, if you can do that.

01:05:09.270 --> 01:05:12.320
So, but that's not
the same as the kind

01:05:12.320 --> 01:05:13.940
of war we've got in Syria today.

01:05:13.940 --> 01:05:15.240
That's for sure.

01:05:15.240 --> 01:05:20.220
&gt;&gt; Jane McAuliffe: I think
we have time for one more?

01:05:20.220 --> 01:05:21.520
&gt;&gt; Yes, sir.

01:05:21.520 --> 01:05:23.140
I'm Ronald Wilson with Social
Security Administration.

01:05:23.140 --> 01:05:29.460
The question I have is do you ever
envision a scenario in the future

01:05:29.460 --> 01:05:34.790
when all nations would be
stable and that the burden of R

01:05:34.790 --> 01:05:38.680
to P would be adhered
to by all nations

01:05:38.680 --> 01:05:41.980
so that there would not be a
flow of refugees, or do you think

01:05:41.980 --> 01:05:45.700
because of the history of
humanity that the burden of R

01:05:45.700 --> 01:05:49.020
to P will always be on the
international community?

01:05:50.120 --> 01:05:51.950
&gt;&gt; Dr. David Hollenbach:
Well, I would love to think

01:05:51.950 --> 01:05:53.680
that we could move
in that direction.

01:05:53.680 --> 01:05:57.710
I'm not enormously hopeful
that we're getting there.

01:05:57.710 --> 01:06:02.760
I do think that there's likely to
be some continuing serious conflict

01:06:02.760 --> 01:06:05.840
and that's one of the
reasons why I have argued

01:06:05.840 --> 01:06:11.000 position:56%
for why we have these positive
duties to take action to help people

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:14.270
who are facing these
crisis situations.

01:06:14.270 --> 01:06:16.810
Negatively, I would like to
think we could get people

01:06:16.810 --> 01:06:21.310
to be serious enough about
adhering to the Geneva Conventions

01:06:21.310 --> 01:06:24.720
and the U.N. Charter and so forth,

01:06:24.720 --> 01:06:27.710
that we wouldn't have
these kinds of conflicts.

01:06:27.710 --> 01:06:35.670
But the fact that I'm not
expecting that to happen real soon,

01:06:35.670 --> 01:06:40.600
is a reason why I've -- arguing
for some of these positive duties

01:06:40.600 --> 01:06:44.660
to respond when crises do emerge.

01:06:44.660 --> 01:06:49.460
I do think that we have to
press much more strongly

01:06:49.460 --> 01:06:54.310
for these implementation of some
of these international standards.

01:06:54.310 --> 01:06:58.220
And I think that the United States
has been contributing to that,

01:06:58.220 --> 01:07:00.980
but we have not always stayed --

01:07:00.980 --> 01:07:04.950
we haven't stayed in harmony
with the Geneva Conventions

01:07:04.950 --> 01:07:07.350
in what we've done with
torture, for example.

01:07:07.350 --> 01:07:11.220
There have been some really serious
problems there, and that's --

01:07:11.220 --> 01:07:13.290
you can make a very strong case

01:07:13.290 --> 01:07:18.410 position:56%
that the U.S. has violated the
Geneva Conventions regarding torture

01:07:18.410 --> 01:07:20.280
of Common Article 3.

01:07:20.280 --> 01:07:24.290
But anyway, my hope is that
we can move in that direction,

01:07:24.290 --> 01:07:26.740
but if you're asking me
to make a prediction,

01:07:26.740 --> 01:07:29.640
I'm not really predicting that
it's going to happen tomorrow.

01:07:29.640 --> 01:07:33.690
But maybe over the -- the
creation of new structures

01:07:33.690 --> 01:07:37.750
of international governance is
really important in this regard.

01:07:37.750 --> 01:07:40.270
And I think that's where the
International Criminal Court is a

01:07:40.270 --> 01:07:42.070
step in the right direction.

01:07:42.070 --> 01:07:44.810
Far from complete, but it's a step.

01:07:44.810 --> 01:07:49.860
So I'd hope to see we can move
further in that direction.

01:07:49.860 --> 01:07:52.170
So.

01:07:52.170 --> 01:07:53.680
&gt;&gt; Jane McAuliffe: Thank you.

01:07:53.680 --> 01:07:56.850
Thank you again, and
please, would you join me

01:07:56.850 --> 01:07:59.340
in thanking our distinguished
lecturer this afternoon.

01:07:59.340 --> 01:08:01.510
Thank you, Dr. Hollenbach.

